  "prompt": "What is the best way to substitute celery seeds in a recipe?",
  "response": "If you need to substitute celery seeds in a recipe, there are several suitable alternatives that can bring a similar flavor to your dish:\n\n- **Celery leaves or stalks**: Fresh celery parts can add the same flavor profile, though you'll need to adjust the quantity since they are not as potent as celery seeds. Use about two to three times the amount of fresh celery as you would seeds.\n\n- **Celery salt**: It combines ground celery seeds with salt. Be mindful of the additional salt, and adjust the overall salt content in your recipe accordingly. Generally, use the same amount of celery salt as you would celery seeds, but reduce other salt sources in the recipe.\n\n- **Dill seeds**: Although they impart a slightly different flavor, dill seeds can work well in place of celery seeds. They have a distinct but somewhat similar taste and can be used in equal amounts.\n\n- **Caraway seeds**: These also have a strong and unique flavor that can complement many dishes in place of celery seeds. Use an equal amount as a substitute.\n\n- **Fennel seeds**: Another alternative with a distinct taste, fennel seeds are slightly sweeter but can work as a substitute when used sparingly. You might want to start with a lesser amount than indicated and adjust based on taste.\n\nWhen substituting, always consider the specific flavor profile and intensity each alternative lends to the dish, and make adjustments to balance the flavors according to your preference.",
